# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chandler-wobble
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] On May 28, 2002 (sol 210), NASA reported that *Odyssey*'s GRS instrument had detected large amounts of hydrogen, a sign that there must be ice lying within a meter of the planet's surface, and proceeded to map the distribution of water below the shallow surface.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] The orbiter also discovered vast deposits of bulk water ice near the surface of equatorial regions.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] In August 2000, NASA solicited candidate names for the mission.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] Out of 200 names submitted, the committee chose Astrobiological Reconnaissance and Elemental Surveyor, abbreviated ARES (a tribute to Ares, the Greek god of war).
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] Faced with criticism that this name was not very compelling, and too aggressive, the naming committee reconvened.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] The candidate name "2001 Mars Odyssey" had earlier been rejected because of copyright and trademark concerns.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] Clarke in Sri Lanka, who responded that he would be delighted to have the mission named after his books, and he had no objections.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] On September 20, NASA associate administrator Ed Weiler wrote to the associate administrator for public affairs recommending a name change from ARES to *2001 Mars Odyssey*.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] Peggy Wilhide then approved the name change.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] Aerobraking ended in January 2002, and Odyssey began its science mapping mission on February 19, 2002.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] *Odyssey*'s original, nominal mission lasted until August 2004, but repeated mission extensions have kept the mission active.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] The payload's MARIE radiation experiment stopped taking measurements after a large solar event bombarded the *Odyssey* spacecraft on October 28, 2003.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] Engineers believe the most likely cause is that a computer chip was damaged by a solar particle smashing into the MARIE computer board.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] About 85% of images and other data from NASA's twin Mars Exploration Rovers, *Spirit* and *Opportunity*, have reached Earth via communications relay by *Odyssey*.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] The orbiter helped analyze potential landing sites for the rovers and performed the same task for NASA's Phoenix mission, which landed on Mars in May 2008.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] *Odyssey* aided NASA's *Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter*, which reached Mars in March 2006, by monitoring atmospheric conditions during months when the newly arrived orbiter used aerobraking to alter its orbit into the desired shape.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] By December 15, 2010, it broke the record for longest serving spacecraft at Mars, with 3,340 days of operation.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] The orbiter's orientation is controlled by a set of three reaction wheels and a spare.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] When one failed in June 2012, the fourth was spun up and successfully brought into service.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] Since July 2012, *Odyssey* has been back in full, nominal operation mode following three weeks of 'safe' mode on remote maintenance.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] On February 11, 2014, mission control accelerated *Odyssey*'s drift toward a morning-daylight orbit to "enable observation of changing ground temperatures after sunrise and after sunset in thousands of places on Mars".
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] The orbital change occurred gradually until November 2015.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] Those observations could yield insight about the composition of the ground and about temperature-driven processes, such as warm seasonal flows observed on some slopes, and geysers fed by spring thawing of carbon dioxide (CO2) ice near Mars's poles.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] On October 19, 2014, NASA reported that the *Mars Odyssey* Orbiter, as well as the *Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter* and *MAVEN*, were healthy after the Comet Siding Spring flyby.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] In 2010, a spokesman for NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory stated that *Odyssey* could continue operating until at least 2016.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] This estimate has since been extended to the end of 2025.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] By 2008, *Mars Odyssey* had mapped the basic distribution of water below the shallow surface.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] The ground truth for its measurements came on July 31, 2008, when NASA announced that the Phoenix lander confirmed the presence of water on Mars, as predicted in 2002 based on data from the *Odyssey* orbiter.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] The science team is trying to determine whether the water ice ever thaws enough to be available for microscopic life, and if carbon-containing chemicals and other raw materials for life are present.
[src:chandler-wobble/2001-mars-odyssey] Evidence for equatorial hydration is both morphological and compositional and is seen at both the Medusae Fossae formation and the Tharsis Montes.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The three-dimensional angular momentum for a point particle is classically represented as a pseudovector **r** × **p**, the cross product of the particle's position vector **r** (relative to some origin) and its momentum vector; the latter is **p** = *m***v** in Newtonian mechanics.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Unlike linear momentum, angular momentum depends on where this origin is chosen, since the particle's position is measured from it.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Angular momentum is an extensive quantity; that is, the total angular momentum of any composite system is the sum of the angular momenta of its constituent parts.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] For a continuous rigid body or a fluid, the total angular momentum is the volume integral of angular momentum density (angular momentum per unit volume in the limit as volume shrinks to zero) over the entire body.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Similar to conservation of linear momentum, where it is conserved if there is no external force, angular momentum is conserved if there is no external torque.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Torque can be defined as the rate of change of angular momentum, analogous to force.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The net *external* torque on any system is always equal to the *total* torque on the system; the sum of all internal torques of any system is always 0 (this is the rotational analogue of Newton's third law of motion).
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Therefore, for an isolated system (where there is no net external torque), the *total* torque on the system must be 0, which means that the total angular momentum of the system is constant.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The change in angular momentum for a particular interaction is called **angular impulse**, sometimes **twirl**.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Angular impulse is the angular analog of (linear) impulse.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The trivial case of the angular momentum L of a body in an orbit is given by $L=2\pi Mfr^{2}$ where M is the mass of the orbiting object, f is the orbit's frequency and r is the orbit's radius.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The angular momentum L of a uniform rigid sphere rotating around its axis, instead, is given by $L={\frac {4}{5}}\pi Mfr^{2}$ where M is the sphere's mass, f is the frequency of rotation and r is the sphere's radius.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Thus, for example, the orbital angular momentum of the Earth with respect to the Sun is about 2.66 × 1040 kg⋅m2⋅s−1, while its rotational angular momentum is about 7.05 × 1033 kg⋅m2⋅s−1.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In the case of a uniform rigid sphere rotating around its axis, if, instead of its mass, its density is known, the angular momentum L is given by $L={\frac {16}{15}}\pi ^{2}\rho fr^{5}$ where $\rho$ is the sphere's density, f is the frequency of rotation and r is the sphere's radius.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In the simplest case of a spinning disk, the angular momentum L is given by $L=\pi Mfr^{2}$ where M is the disk's mass, f is the frequency of rotation and r is the disk's radius.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Just as for angular velocity, there are two special types of angular momentum of an object: the **spin angular momentum** is the angular momentum about the object's center of mass, while the **orbital angular momentum** is the angular momentum about a chosen center of rotation.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The Earth has an orbital angular momentum by nature of revolving around the Sun, and a spin angular momentum by nature of its daily rotation around the polar axis.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The total angular momentum is the sum of the spin and orbital angular momenta.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In the case of the Earth the primary conserved quantity is the total angular momentum of the Solar System because angular momentum is exchanged to a small but important extent among the planets and the Sun.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The orbital angular momentum vector of a point particle is always parallel and directly proportional to its orbital angular velocity vector **ω**, where the constant of proportionality depends on both the mass of the particle and its distance from origin.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The spin angular momentum vector of a rigid body is proportional but not always parallel to the spin angular velocity vector **Ω**, making the constant of proportionality a second-rank tensor rather than a scalar.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Angular momentum is a vector quantity (more precisely, a pseudovector) that represents the product of a body's rotational inertia and rotational velocity (in radians/sec) about a particular axis.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] However, if the particle's trajectory lies in a single plane, it is sufficient to discard the vector nature of angular momentum, and treat it as a scalar (more precisely, a pseudoscalar).
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Angular momentum can be considered a rotational analog of linear momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Unlike mass, which depends only on amount of matter, moment of inertia depends also on the position of the axis of rotation and the distribution of the matter.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Unlike linear velocity, which does not depend upon the choice of origin, orbital angular velocity is always measured with respect to a fixed origin.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Therefore, strictly speaking, L should be referred to as the angular momentum *relative to that center*.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] the product of the radius of rotation r and the linear momentum of the particle $p=mv$ , where $v=r\omega$ is the linear (tangential) speed.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] This simple analysis can also apply to non-circular motion if one uses the component of the motion perpendicular to the radius vector: $L=rmv_{\perp },$ where $v_{\perp }=v\sin(\theta )$ is the perpendicular component of the motion.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Expanding, $L=rmv\sin(\theta ),$ rearranging, $L=r\sin(\theta )mv,$ and reducing, angular momentum can also be expressed, $L=r_{\perp }mv,$ where $r_{\perp }=r\sin(\theta )$ is the length of the *moment arm*, a line dropped perpendicularly from the origin onto the path of the particle.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] It is this definition, (length of moment arm) × (linear momentum), to which the term *moment of momentum* refers.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Another approach is to define angular momentum as the conjugate momentum (also called **canonical momentum**) of the angular coordinate $\phi$ expressed in the Lagrangian of the mechanical system.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Consider a mechanical system with a mass m constrained to move in a circle of radius r in the absence of any external force field.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] By retaining this vector nature of angular momentum, the general nature of the equations is also retained, and can describe any sort of three-dimensional motion about the center of rotation – circular, linear, or otherwise.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] By the definition of the cross product, the $\mathbf {L}$ vector is perpendicular to both $\mathbf {r}$ and $\mathbf {p}$ .
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] It is directed perpendicular to the plane of angular displacement, as indicated by the right-hand rule – so that the angular velocity is seen as counter-clockwise from the head of the vector.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Conversely, the $\mathbf {L}$ vector defines the plane in which $\mathbf {r}$ and $\mathbf {p}$ lie.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Angular momentum can be described as the rotational analog of linear momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Like linear momentum it involves elements of mass and displacement.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Unlike linear momentum it also involves elements of position and shape.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Many problems in physics involve matter in motion about some certain point in space, be it in actual rotation about it, or simply moving past it, where it is desired to know what effect the moving matter has on the point—can it exert energy upon it or perform work about it?
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Energy, the ability to do work, can be stored in matter by setting it in motion—a combination of its inertia and its displacement.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Inertia is measured by its mass, and displacement by its velocity.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Their product, ${\begin{aligned}({\text{amount of inertia}})\times ({\text{amount of displacement}})&={\text{amount of (inertia⋅displacement)}}\\{\text{mass}}\times {\text{velocity}}&={\text{momentum}}\\m\times v&=p\\\end{aligned}}$ is the matter's momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Referring this momentum to a central point introduces a complication: the momentum is not applied to the point directly.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] For instance, a particle of matter at the outer edge of a wheel is, in effect, at the end of a lever of the same length as the wheel's radius, its momentum turning the lever about the center point.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] This imaginary lever is known as the *moment arm*.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] It has the effect of multiplying the momentum's effort in proportion to its length, an effect known as a *moment*.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The equation $L=rmv$ combines a moment (a mass m turning moment arm r ) with a linear (straight-line equivalent) speed v .
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Linear speed referred to the central point is simply the product of the distance r and the angular speed $\omega$ versus the point: $v=r\omega ,$ another moment.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Hence, angular momentum contains a double moment: $L=rmr\omega .$ Simplifying slightly, $L=r^{2}m\omega ,$ the quantity $r^{2}m$ is the particle's moment of inertia, sometimes called the second moment of mass.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The direction of momentum is related to the direction of the velocity for linear movement.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The direction of angular momentum is related to the angular velocity of the rotation.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Because moment of inertia is a crucial part of the spin angular momentum, the latter necessarily includes all of the complications of the former, which is calculated by multiplying elementary bits of the mass by the squares of their distances from the center of rotation.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Therefore, the total moment of inertia, and the angular momentum, is a complex function of the configuration of the matter about the center of rotation and the orientation of the rotation for the various bits.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] For a rigid body, for instance a wheel or an asteroid, the orientation of rotation is simply the position of the rotation axis versus the matter of the body.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] It may or may not pass through the center of mass, or it may lie completely outside of the body.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] For the same body, angular momentum may take a different value for every possible axis about which rotation may take place.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] It reaches a minimum when the axis passes through the center of mass.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] For a collection of objects revolving about a center, for instance all of the bodies of the Solar System, the orientations may be somewhat organized, as is the Solar System, with most of the bodies' axes lying close to the system's axis.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Their orientations may also be completely random.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In brief, the more mass and the farther it is from the center of rotation (the longer the moment arm), the greater the moment of inertia, and therefore the greater the angular momentum for a given angular velocity.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In many cases the moment of inertia, and hence the angular momentum, can be simplified by, $I=k^{2}m,$ where k is the radius of gyration, the distance from the axis at which the entire mass m may be considered as concentrated.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Angular momentum's dependence on position and shape is reflected in its units versus linear momentum: kg⋅m2/s or N⋅m⋅s for angular momentum versus kg⋅m/s or N⋅s for linear momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] When calculating angular momentum as the product of the moment of inertia times the angular velocity, the angular velocity must be expressed in radians per second, where the radian assumes the dimensionless value of unity.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] (When performing dimensional analysis, it may be productive to use orientational analysis which treats radians as a base unit, but this is not done in the International system of units).
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The units of angular momentum can be interpreted as torque⋅time.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] An object with angular momentum of *L* N⋅m⋅s can be reduced to zero angular velocity by an angular impulse of *L* N⋅m⋅s.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The plane perpendicular to the axis of angular momentum and passing through the center of mass is sometimes called the *invariable plane*, because the direction of the axis remains fixed if only the interactions of the bodies within the system, free from outside influences, are considered.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] One such plane is the invariable plane of the Solar System.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Newton's second law of motion can be expressed mathematically, $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a} ,$ or force = mass × acceleration.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Note that the torque is not necessarily proportional or parallel to the angular acceleration (as one might expect).
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The reason for this is that the moment of inertia of a particle can change with time, something that cannot occur for ordinary mass.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The conservation of angular momentum is used in analyzing *central force motion*.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] If the net force on some body is directed always toward some point, the *center*, then there is no torque on the body with respect to the center, as all of the force is directed along the radius vector, and none is perpendicular to the radius.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Mathematically, torque ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}=\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {F} =\mathbf {0} ,$ because in this case $\mathbf {r}$ and $\mathbf {F}$ are parallel vectors.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Therefore, the angular momentum of the body about the center is constant.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] This is the case with gravitational attraction in the orbits of planets and satellites, where the gravitational force is always directed toward the primary body and orbiting bodies conserve angular momentum by exchanging distance and velocity as they move about the primary.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Central force motion is also used in the analysis of the Bohr model of the atom.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] For a planet, angular momentum is distributed between the spin of the planet and its revolution in its orbit, and these are often exchanged by various mechanisms.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The conservation of angular momentum in the Earth–Moon system results in the transfer of angular momentum from Earth to Moon, due to tidal torque the Moon exerts on the Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] This in turn results in the slowing down of the rotation rate of Earth, at about 65.7 nanoseconds per day, and in gradual increase of the radius of Moon's orbit, at about 3.82 centimeters per year.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The conservation of angular momentum explains the angular acceleration of an ice skater as they bring their arms and legs close to the vertical axis of rotation.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] By bringing part of the mass of their body closer to the axis, they decrease their body's moment of inertia.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Because angular momentum is the product of moment of inertia and angular velocity, if the angular momentum remains constant (is conserved), then the angular velocity (rotational speed) of the skater must increase.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The same phenomenon results in extremely fast spin of compact stars (like white dwarfs, neutron stars and black holes) when they are formed out of much larger and slower rotating stars.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Conservation is not always a full explanation for the dynamics of a system but is a key constraint.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] For example, a spinning top is subject to gravitational torque making it lean over and change the angular momentum about the nutation axis, but neglecting friction at the point of spinning contact, it has a conserved angular momentum about its spinning axis, and another about its precession axis.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Also, in any planetary system, the planets, star(s), comets, and asteroids can all move in numerous complicated ways, but only so that the angular momentum of the system is conserved.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Noether's theorem states that every conservation law is associated with a symmetry (invariant) of the underlying physics.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The symmetry associated with conservation of angular momentum is rotational invariance.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The fact that the physics of a system is unchanged if it is rotated by any angle about an axis implies that angular momentum is conserved.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Indeed, given initial conditions of position and velocity for every point, and the forces at such a condition, one may use Newton's second law to calculate the second derivative of position, and solving for this gives full information on the development of the physical system with time.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Note, however, that this is no longer true in quantum mechanics, due to the existence of particle spin, which is an angular momentum that cannot be described by the cumulative effect of point-like motions in space.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] As an example, consider decreasing of the moment of inertia, e.g. when a figure skater is pulling in their hands, speeding up the circular motion.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Using this, we see that the change requires an energy of: $dE=d\left({\tfrac {1}{2}}I\cdot \omega ^{2}\right)={\tfrac {1}{2}}dI\cdot \omega ^{2}+I\cdot \omega \cdot d\omega =-{\tfrac {1}{2}}dI\cdot \omega ^{2}$ so that a decrease in the moment of inertia requires investing energy.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] This can be compared to the work done as calculated using Newton's laws.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Let us observe a point of mass *m*, whose position vector relative to the center of motion is perpendicular to the z-axis at a given point of time, and is at a distance *z*.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] For a non-pointlike body one must integrate over this, with *m* replaced by the mass density per unit *z*.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] This gives: $dW=-{\tfrac {1}{2}}dI\cdot \omega ^{2}$ which is exactly the energy required for keeping the angular momentum conserved.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Note, that the above calculation can also be performed per mass, using kinematics only.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] However, this is different when pulling the palms closer to the body: The acceleration due to rotation now increases the speed; but because of the rotation, the increase in speed does not translate to a significant speed inwards, but to an increase of the rotation speed.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In classical mechanics it can be shown that the rotational invariance of action functionals implies conservation of angular momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The action is defined in classical physics as a functional of positions, $x_{i}(t)$ often represented by the use of square brackets, and the final and initial times.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] If the action is invariant of an infinitesimal transformation, it can be mathematically stated as: ${\textstyle \delta S=S\left([x_{i}+\delta x_{i}];t_{1},t_{2}\right)-S\left([x_{i}];t_{1},t_{2}\right)=0}$ .
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] This corresponds to the conservation of angular momentum throughout the motion.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In Lagrangian mechanics, angular momentum for rotation around a given axis, is the conjugate momentum of the generalized coordinate of the angle around the same axis.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] For example, $L_{z}$ , the angular momentum around the z axis, is: $L_{z}={\frac {\partial {\cal {L}}}{\partial {\dot {\theta }}_{z}}}$ where ${\cal {L}}$ is the Lagrangian and $\theta _{z}$ is the angle around the z axis.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Note that ${\dot {\theta }}_{z}$ , the time derivative of the angle, is the angular velocity $\omega _{z}$ .
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Since the lagrangian is dependent upon the angles of the object only through the potential, we have: ${\frac {d{L_{z}}_{i}}{dt}}={\frac {\partial {\cal {L}}}{\partial {{\theta _{z}}_{i}}}}=-{\frac {\partial V}{\partial {{\theta _{z}}_{i}}}}$ which is the torque on the *i*th object.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Suppose the system is invariant to rotations, so that the potential is independent of an overall rotation by the angle *θ*z (thus it may depend on the angles of objects only through their differences, in the form $V({\theta _{z}}_{i},{\theta _{z}}_{j})=V({\theta _{z}}_{i}-{\theta _{z}}_{j})$ ).
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] We therefore get for the total angular momentum: ${\frac {dL_{z}}{dt}}=-{\frac {\partial V}{\partial {\theta _{z}}}}=0$ And thus the angular momentum around the z-axis is conserved.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] This analysis can be repeated separately for each axis, giving conservation of the angular momentum vector.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] However, the angles around the three axes cannot be treated simultaneously as generalized coordinates, since they are not independent; in particular, two angles per point suffice to determine its position.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] While it is true that in the case of a rigid body, fully describing it requires, in addition to three translational degrees of freedom, also specification of three rotational degrees of freedom; however these cannot be defined as rotations around the Cartesian axes (see Euler angles).
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] This caveat is reflected in quantum mechanics in the non-trivial commutation relations of the different components of the angular momentum operator.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Equivalently, in Hamiltonian mechanics the Hamiltonian can be described as a function of the angular momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] And so we get the same results as in the Lagrangian formalism.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] This form of the kinetic energy part of the Hamiltonian is useful in analyzing central potential problems, and is easily transformed to a quantum mechanical work frame (e.g. in the hydrogen atom problem).
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] While in classical mechanics the language of angular momentum can be replaced by Newton's laws of motion, it is particularly useful for motion in central potential such as planetary motion in the solar system.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Thus, the orbit of a planet in the solar system is defined by its energy, angular momentum and angles of the orbit major axis relative to a coordinate frame.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In astrodynamics and celestial mechanics, a quantity closely related to angular momentum is defined as $\mathbf {h} =\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {v} ,$ called *specific angular momentum*.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Note that $\mathbf {L} =m\mathbf {h} .$ Mass is often unimportant in orbital mechanics calculations, because motion of a body is determined by gravity.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The primary body of the system is often so much larger than any bodies in motion about it that the gravitational effect of the smaller bodies on it can be neglected; it maintains, in effect, constant velocity.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The motion of all bodies is affected by its gravity in the same way, regardless of mass, and therefore all move approximately the same way under the same conditions.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Angular momentum is also an extremely useful concept for describing rotating rigid bodies such as a gyroscope or a rocky planet.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] For a continuous mass distribution with density function *ρ*(**r**), a differential volume element *dV* with position vector **r** within the mass has a mass element *dm* = *ρ*(**r**)*dV*.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In the derivation which follows, integrals similar to this can replace the sums for the case of continuous mass.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] For a collection of particles in motion about an arbitrary origin, it is informative to develop the equation of angular momentum by resolving their motion into components about their own center of mass and about the origin.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The first term is the angular momentum of the center of mass relative to the origin.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Similar to *§ Single particle*, below, it is the angular momentum of one particle of mass *M* at the center of mass moving with velocity **V**.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The second term is the angular momentum of the particles moving relative to the center of mass, similar to *§ Fixed center of mass*, below.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The result is general—the motion of the particles is not restricted to rotation or revolution about the origin or center of mass.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The particles need not be individual masses, but can be elements of a continuous distribution, such as a solid body.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In modern (20th century) theoretical physics, angular momentum (not including any intrinsic angular momentum – see below) is described using a different formalism, instead of a classical pseudovector.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In this formalism, angular momentum is the 2-form Noether charge associated with rotational invariance.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] As a result, angular momentum is generally not conserved locally for general curved spacetimes, unless they have rotational symmetry; whereas globally the notion of angular momentum itself only makes sense if the spacetime is asymptotically flat.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In classical mechanics, the angular momentum of a particle can be reinterpreted as a plane element: $\mathbf {L} =\mathbf {r} \wedge \mathbf {p} \,,$ in which the exterior product (∧) replaces the cross product (×) (these products have similar characteristics but are nonequivalent).
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] This has the advantage of a clearer geometric interpretation as a plane element, defined using the vectors **x** and **p**, and the expression is true in any number of dimensions.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] The angular velocity can also be defined as an anti-symmetric second order tensor, with components *ωij*.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] Again, this equation in **L** and ***ω*** as tensors is true in any number of dimensions.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] This equation also appears in the geometric algebra formalism, in which **L** and ***ω*** are bivectors, and the moment of inertia is a mapping between them.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p01] In each of the above cases, for a system of particles the total angular momentum is just the sum of the individual particle angular momenta, and the center of mass is for the system.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] In quantum mechanics, angular momentum (like other quantities) is expressed as an operator, and its one-dimensional projections have quantized eigenvalues.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Angular momentum is subject to the Heisenberg uncertainty principle, implying that at any time, only one projection (also called "component") can be measured with definite precision; the other two then remain uncertain.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Because of this, the axis of rotation of a quantum particle is undefined.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Quantum particles *do* possess a type of non-orbital angular momentum called "spin", but this angular momentum does not correspond to a spinning motion.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] In relativistic quantum mechanics the above relativistic definition becomes a tensorial operator.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] The classical definition of angular momentum as $\mathbf {L} =\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {p}$ can be carried over to quantum mechanics, by reinterpreting **r** as the quantum position operator and **p** as the quantum momentum operator.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] **L** is then an operator, specifically called the *orbital angular momentum operator*.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] The components of the angular momentum operator satisfy the commutation relations of the Lie algebra SO(3).
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Indeed, these operators are precisely the infinitesimal action of the rotation group on the quantum Hilbert space.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] However, in quantum physics, there is another type of angular momentum, called *spin angular momentum*, represented by the spin operator **S**.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Spin is often depicted as a particle literally spinning around an axis, but this is a misleading and inaccurate picture: spin is an intrinsic property of a particle, unrelated to any sort of motion in space and fundamentally different from orbital angular momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] All elementary particles have a characteristic spin, which is nonzero for all elementary particles other than the Higgs boson (which has spin 0, making it the only known elementary scalar boson).
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] For example, electrons have "spin 1/2" (this actually means "spin ħ/2"), photons have "spin 1" (this actually means "spin ħ"), and pi-mesons have spin 0.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Finally, there is total angular momentum **J**, which combines both the spin and orbital angular momentum of all particles and fields.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] (For one particle, **J** = **L** + **S**.) Conservation of angular momentum applies to **J**, but not to **L** or **S**; for example, the spin–orbit interaction allows angular momentum to transfer back and forth between **L** and **S**, with the total remaining constant.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Electrons and photons need not have integer-based values for total angular momentum, but can also have half-integer values.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] In molecules the total angular momentum **F** is the sum of the rovibronic (orbital) angular momentum **N**, the electron spin angular momentum **S**, and the nuclear spin angular momentum **I**.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] For electronic singlet states the rovibronic angular momentum is denoted **J** rather than **N**.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] As explained by Van Vleck, the components of the molecular rovibronic angular momentum referred to molecule-fixed axes have different commutation relations from those for the components about space-fixed axes.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] In quantum mechanics, angular momentum is quantized – that is, it cannot vary continuously, but only in "quantum leaps" between certain allowed values.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] The reduced Planck constant $\hbar$ is tiny by everyday standards, about 10−34 J s, and therefore this quantization does not noticeably affect the angular momentum of macroscopic objects.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] However, it is very important in the microscopic world.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] For example, the structure of electron shells and subshells in chemistry is significantly affected by the quantization of angular momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Quantization of angular momentum was first postulated by Niels Bohr in his model of the atom and was later predicted by Erwin Schrödinger in his Schrödinger equation.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] In the definition $\mathbf {L} =\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {p}$ , six operators are involved: The position operators $r_{x}$ , $r_{y}$ , $r_{z}$ , and the momentum operators $p_{x}$ , $p_{y}$ , $p_{z}$ .
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] However, the Heisenberg uncertainty principle tells us that it is not possible for all six of these quantities to be known simultaneously with arbitrary precision.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Therefore, there are limits to what can be known or measured about a particle's angular momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] It turns out that the best that one can do is to simultaneously measure both the angular momentum vector's magnitude and its component along one axis.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] The uncertainty is closely related to the fact that different components of an angular momentum operator do not commute, for example $L_{x}L_{y}\neq L_{y}L_{x}$ .
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] As mentioned above, orbital angular momentum **L** is defined as in classical mechanics: $\mathbf {L} =\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {p}$ , but *total* angular momentum **J** is defined in a different, more basic way: **J** is defined as the "generator of rotations".
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] More specifically, **J** is defined so that the operator $R({\hat {n}},\phi )\equiv \exp \left(-{\frac {i}{\hbar }}\phi \,\mathbf {J} \cdot {\hat {\mathbf {n} }}\right)$ is the rotation operator that takes any system and rotates it by angle $\phi$ about the axis ${\hat {\mathbf {n} }}$ .
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] (The "exp" in the formula refers to operator exponential.) To put this the other way around, whatever our quantum Hilbert space is, we expect that the rotation group SO(3) will act on it.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] There is then an associated action of the Lie algebra so(3) of SO(3); the operators describing the action of so(3) on our Hilbert space are the (total) angular momentum operators.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] The relationship between the angular momentum operator and the rotation operators is the same as the relationship between Lie algebras and Lie groups in mathematics.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] The close relationship between angular momentum and rotations is reflected in Noether's theorem that proves that angular momentum is conserved whenever the laws of physics are rotationally invariant.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] When describing the motion of a charged particle in an electromagnetic field, the canonical momentum **P** (derived from the Lagrangian for this system) is not gauge invariant.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] As a consequence, the canonical angular momentum **L** = **r** × **P** is not gauge invariant either.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Instead, the momentum that is physical, the so-called *kinetic momentum* (used throughout this article), is (in SI units) $\mathbf {p} =m\mathbf {v} =\mathbf {P} -e\mathbf {A}$ where *e* is the electric charge of the particle and **A** the magnetic vector potential of the electromagnetic field.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] The interplay with quantum mechanics is discussed further in the article on canonical commutation relations.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] The above identities are valid *locally*, i.e. in each space point $\mathbf {r}$ in a given moment t .
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Tropical cyclones and other related weather phenomena involve conservation of angular momentum in order to explain the dynamics.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Winds revolve slowly around low pressure systems, mainly due to the coriolis effect.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] If the low pressure intensifies and the slowly circulating air is drawn toward the center, the molecules must speed up in order to conserve angular momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] By the time they reach the center, the speeds become destructive.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Johannes Kepler determined the laws of planetary motion without knowledge of conservation of momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] However, not long after his discovery their derivation was determined from conservation of angular momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Planets move more slowly the further they are out in their elliptical orbits, which is explained intuitively by the fact that orbital angular momentum is proportional to the radius of the orbit.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Since the mass does not change and the angular momentum is conserved, the velocity drops.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Tidal acceleration is an effect of the tidal forces between an orbiting natural satellite (e.g. the Moon) and the primary planet that it orbits (e.g.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] The Earth loses angular momentum which is transferred to the Moon such that the overall angular momentum is conserved.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Examples of using conservation of angular momentum for practical advantage are abundant.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] In engines such as steam engines or internal combustion engines, a flywheel is needed to efficiently convert the lateral motion of the pistons to rotational motion.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Inertial navigation systems explicitly use the fact that angular momentum is conserved with respect to the inertial frame of space.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Inertial navigation is what enables submarine trips under the polar ice cap, but are also crucial to all forms of modern navigation.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Rifled bullets use the stability provided by conservation of angular momentum to be more true in their trajectory.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] The invention of rifled firearms and cannons gave their users significant strategic advantage in battle, and thus were a technological turning point in history.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] However, his geometric proof of the law of areas is an outstanding example of Newton's genius, and indirectly proves angular momentum conservation in the case of a central force.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] As a planet orbits the Sun, the line between the Sun and the planet sweeps out equal areas in equal intervals of time.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] This had been known since Kepler expounded his second law of planetary motion.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Newton derived a unique geometric proof, and went on to show that the attractive force of the Sun's gravity was the cause of all of Kepler's laws.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] During the first interval of time, an object is in motion from point **A** to point **B**.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Undisturbed, it would continue to point **c** during the second interval.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] When the object arrives at **B**, it receives an impulse directed toward point **S**.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] The impulse gives it a small added velocity toward **S**, such that if this were its only velocity, it would move from **B** to **V** during the second interval.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] By the rules of velocity composition, these two velocities add, and point **C** is found by construction of parallelogram **BcCV**.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Thus the object's path is deflected by the impulse so that it arrives at point **C** at the end of the second interval.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Because the triangles **SBc** and **SBC** have the same base **SB** and the same height **Bc** or **VC**, they have the same area.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] By symmetry, triangle **SBc** also has the same area as triangle **SAB**, therefore the object has swept out equal areas **SAB** and **SBC** in equal times.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] At point **C**, the object receives another impulse toward **S**, again deflecting its path during the third interval from **d** to **D**.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Allowing the time intervals to become ever smaller, the path **ABCDE** approaches indefinitely close to a continuous curve.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Note that because this derivation is geometric, and no specific force is applied, it proves a more general law than Kepler's second law of planetary motion.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] It shows that the Law of Areas applies to any central force, attractive or repulsive, continuous or non-continuous, or zero.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Hence, if the area swept per unit time is constant, then by the triangular area formula ⁠1/2⁠(base)(height), the product (base)(height) and therefore the product *rv*⊥ are constant: if *r* and the base length are decreased, *v*⊥ and height must increase proportionally.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Mass is constant, therefore angular momentum *rmv*⊥ is conserved by this exchange of distance and velocity.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Wherever **C** is eventually located due to the impulse applied at **B**, the product (**SB**)(**VC**), and therefore *rmv*⊥ remain constant.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Another areal proof of conservation of angular momentum for any central force uses Mamikon's sweeping tangents theorem.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Leonhard Euler, Daniel Bernoulli, and Patrick d'Arcy all understood angular momentum in terms of conservation of areal velocity, a result of their analysis of Kepler's second law of planetary motion.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] It is unlikely that they realized the implications for ordinary rotating matter.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] In 1736 Euler, like Newton, touched on some of the equations of angular momentum in his *Mechanica* without further developing them.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Bernoulli wrote in a 1744 letter of a "moment of rotational motion", possibly the first conception of angular momentum as we now understand it.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] In 1799, Pierre-Simon Laplace first realized that a fixed plane was associated with rotation—his *invariable plane*.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Louis Poinsot in 1803 began representing rotations as a line segment perpendicular to the rotation, and elaborated on the "conservation of moments".
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] In 1852 Léon Foucault used a gyroscope in an experiment to display the Earth's rotation.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] In an 1872 edition of the same book, Rankine stated that "The term *angular momentum* was introduced by Mr.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Hayward's article *On a Direct Method of estimating Velocities, Accelerations, and all similar Quantities with respect to Axes moveable in any manner in Space with Applications,* which was introduced in 1856, and published in 1864.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Rankine was mistaken, as numerous publications feature the term starting in the late 18th to early 19th centuries.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] However, Hayward's article apparently was the first use of the term and the concept seen by much of the English-speaking world.
[src:chandler-wobble/angular-momentum-p02] Before this, angular momentum was typically referred to as "momentum of rotation" in English.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] An **astronomer** is a scientist in the field of astronomy who focuses on a specific question or field outside the scope of Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Astronomers study astronomical objects, such as stars, planets, moons, comets and galaxies, by some combination of observation and the application of astrophysical models.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Examples of topics or fields astronomers study include planetary science, solar astronomy, the origin or evolution of stars, or the formation of galaxies.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] A related but distinct subject is physical cosmology, which studies the universe as a whole.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Astronomers cannot typically perform experiments: the objects of interest in the field are far away.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Consequently they rely primarily on observations, collecting electromagnetic radiation, gravitational waves, or particles such as cosmic rays.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Some experiments on planets in the solar system are now possible via remote controlled spacecraft.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Some of the measurements astronomers perform include astrometry (positions of celestial bodies), photometry (light flux), spectroscopy (intensity vs wavelength), and imaging.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Astronomy includes astrometry, planetary astronomy, astrophysics, astrochemistry, astrobiology, stellar astronomy, galactic astronomy, extragalactic astronomy, and physical cosmology.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Astronomers can also specialize in certain specialties of observational astronomy, such as infrared astronomy, neutrino astronomy, x-ray astronomy, and gravitational-wave astronomy.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Historically, astronomy was more concerned with the classification and description of phenomena in the sky, while astrophysics attempted to explain these phenomena and the differences between them using physical laws.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Today, that distinction has mostly disappeared and the terms "astronomer" and "astrophysicist" are interchangeable.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Professional astronomers are highly educated individuals who typically have a PhD in physics or astronomy and are employed by research institutions or universities.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] They spend the majority of their time working on research, although they quite often have other duties such as teaching, building instruments, or aiding in the operation of an observatory.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] The American Astronomical Society, which is the major organization of professional astronomers in North America, has approximately 8,200 members (as of 2024).
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] This number includes scientists from other fields such as physics, geology, and engineering, whose research interests are closely related to astronomy.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] The International Astronomical Union comprises about 12,700 members from 92 countries who are involved in astronomical research at the PhD level and beyond (as of 2024).
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Contrary to the classical image of an old astronomer peering through a telescope through the dark hours of the night, it is far more common to use a charge-coupled device (CCD) camera to record a long, deep exposure, allowing a more sensitive image to be created because the light is added over time.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Before CCDs, photographic plates were a common method of observation.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Modern astronomers spend relatively little time at telescopes, usually just a few weeks per year.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Analysis of observed phenomena, along with making predictions as to the causes of what they observe, takes the majority of observational astronomers' time.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Astronomers who serve as faculty spend much of their time teaching undergraduate and graduate classes.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Most universities also have outreach programs, including public telescope time and sometimes planetarium, as a public service to encourage interest in the field.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Those who become astronomers usually have a broad background in physics, mathematics, sciences, and computing in high school.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Taking courses that teach how to research, write, and present papers are part of the higher education of an astronomer, while most astronomers attain both a Master's degree and eventually a PhD degree in astronomy, physics or astrophysics.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Throughout the PhD training, a successful student is financially supported with a stipend.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] While there is a relatively low number of professional astronomers, the field is popular among amateurs.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] Most cities have amateur astronomy clubs that meet on a regular basis and often host star parties.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] The Astronomical Society of the Pacific is the largest general astronomical society in the world, comprising both professional and amateur astronomers as well as educators from 70 different nations.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] As with any hobby, most people who practice amateur astronomy may devote a few hours a month to stargazing and reading the latest developments in research.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomer] However, amateurs span the range from so-called "armchair astronomers" to people who own science-grade telescopes and instruments with which they are able to make their own discoveries, create astrophotographs, and assist professional astronomers in research.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] An example of precession and nutation is the variation over time of the orientation of the axis of rotation of the Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] This is important because the most commonly used frame of reference for measurement of the positions of astronomical objects is the Earth's equator — the so-called equatorial coordinate system.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] The effect of precession and nutation causes this frame of reference itself to change over time, relative to an arbitrary fixed frame.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] Nutation is one of the corrections which must be applied to obtain the apparent place of an astronomical object.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] When calculating the position of an object, it is initially expressed relative to the *mean equinox and equator* — defined by the orientation of the Earth's axis at a specified date, taking into account the long-term effect of precession, but *not* the shorter-term effects of nutation.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] It is then necessary to apply a further correction to take into account the effect of nutation, after which the position relative to the *true equinox and equator* is obtained.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] Because the dynamic motions of the planets are so well known, their nutations can be calculated to within arcseconds over periods of many decades.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] Precession and nutation are caused principally by the gravitational forces of the Moon and Sun acting upon the non-spherical figure of the Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] Nutation occurs because the forces are not constant, and vary as the Earth revolves around the Sun, and the Moon revolves around the Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] Basically, there are also torques from other planets that cause planetary precession which contributes to about 2% of the total precession.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] Because of periodic variations in the torques from the sun and the moon, the wobbling (nutation) comes into place.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] You can think of precession as the average and nutation as the instantaneous.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] The largest contributor to nutation is the inclination of the orbit of the Moon around the Earth, at slightly over 5° to the plane of the ecliptic.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] The orientation of this orbital plane varies over a period of about 18.6 years (this period is referred to as the saros).
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] Because the Earth's equator is itself inclined at an angle of about 23.4° to the ecliptic (the obliquity of the ecliptic, $\epsilon$ ), these effects combine to vary the inclination of the Moon's orbit to the equator by between 18.4° and 28.6° over the 18.6 year period.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] This causes the orientation of the Earth's axis to vary over the same period, with the true position of the celestial poles describing a small ellipse around their mean position.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] The maximum radius of this ellipse is the *constant of nutation*, approximately 9.2 arcseconds.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] Smaller effects also contribute to nutation.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] These are caused by the monthly motion of the Moon around the Earth and its orbital eccentricity, and similar terms caused by the annual motion of the Earth around the Sun.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] Because nutation causes a change to the frame of reference, rather than a change in position of an observed object itself, it applies equally to all objects.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] Its magnitude at any point in time is usually expressed in terms of ecliptic coordinates, as *nutation in longitude* ( $\Delta \psi$ ) in seconds of arc and *nutation in obliquity* ( $\Delta \epsilon$ ) in seconds of arc.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] where $\Omega$ is the ecliptic longitude of the ascending node of the Moon's orbit.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] By way of reference, the sum of the absolute value of all the remaining terms is 1.4 arcseconds for longitude and 0.9 arcseconds for obliquity.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] Earth also has an additional 0.10 to 0.15 seconds of arc nutations with a period 6 and half years called Chandler wobble and its due to free nutation caused by irregular distribution of mass around Earth axis.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] Nutation was discovered by James Bradley from a series of observations of stars conducted between 1727 and 1747.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] These observations were originally intended to demonstrate conclusively the existence of the annual aberration of light, a phenomenon that Bradley had unexpectedly discovered in 1725–6.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] However, there were some residual discrepancies in the stars' positions that were not explained by aberration, and Bradley suspected that they were caused by nutation taking place over the 18.6 year period of the revolution of the nodes of the Moon's orbit.
[src:chandler-wobble/astronomical-nutation] This was confirmed by his 20-year series of observations, in which he discovered that the celestial pole moved in a slightly flattened ellipse of 18 by 16 arcseconds about its mean position.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] An **atmosphere** is a layer of gases that envelop an astronomical object, held in place by the gravity of the object.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The name originates from Ancient Greek ἀτμός*(*atmós*)* 'vapour, steam' and σφαῖρα*(*sphaîra*)* 'sphere'.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] An object acquires most of its atmosphere during its primordial epoch, either by accretion of matter or by outgassing of volatiles.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The chemical interaction of the atmosphere with the solid surface can change its fundamental composition, as can photochemical interaction with the Sun.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] A planet retains an atmosphere for longer durations when the gravity is high and the temperature is low.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The solar wind works to strip away a planet's outer atmosphere, although this process is slowed by a magnetosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The further a body is from the Sun, the lower the rate of atmospheric stripping.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Aside from Mercury, all Solar System planets have substantial atmospheres, as does the dwarf planet Pluto and the moon Titan.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The high gravity and low temperature of Jupiter and the other gas giant planets allow them to retain massive atmospheres of mostly hydrogen and helium.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Lower mass terrestrial planets orbit closer to the Sun, and so mainly retain higher molar mass atmospheres made of carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen, with trace amounts of inert gas.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Atmospheres have been detected around exoplanets such as HD 209458 b and Kepler-7b.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] A stellar atmosphere is the outer region of a star, which includes the layers above the opaque photosphere; stars of low temperature might have outer atmospheres containing compound molecules.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Other objects with atmospheres are brown dwarfs and active comets.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] In the nebular hypothesis, stars form during the gravitational collapse of a mass of gas and dust within an interstellar molecular cloud.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] This material forms a pancake-like rotating disk with the mass concentrated at the center.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The protostar is created at the central mass concentration, while the planets and satellites are formed in the disk through a process of accretion.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Dust settles into the median disk plane, forming materials that can collide and accrete to create planetesimals.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Close to the star, these bodies grow and accumulate to form protoplanets consisting primarily of refractory materials with few volatiles.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Further from the star, planetary embryos are created from accumulation of volatiles up to around ten times the mass of the Earth or more.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Masses of gas are then acquired from the surrounding disk nebula, forming a gas giant around the embryo.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Planetary satellites form in a similar fashion from the disk of material around the planets.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The primary atmosphere of a planet is produced when the gravity is sufficient to retain accreted gas against escape processes.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The latter can include collisions with other bodies that impart sufficient energy for the gasses to escape.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For the terrestrial planets, the high temperatures generated by their initial bombardment results in the outgassing of volatiles, creating the secondary atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The original composition and thickness of the atmosphere is thus determined by the stellar nebula's chemistry and temperature, but can be modified by processes within the astronomical body that release different atmospheric components.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The circumstellar disk will finally dissipate on time scales of about 107 years, and the star will complete its contraction then ignite hydrogen fusion at its core in a time frame determined by its mass.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The atmospheres of the planets Venus and Mars are principally composed of carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and argon.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Because Venus has no oceans or rain to dissolve the carbon dioxide, large amounts of this greenhouse gas has remained in the atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The result is a dense atmosphere about 80 times the pressure of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The planet's lack of a magnetic field and closer proximity to the Sun resulted in the loss of its hydrogen (in the form of water) after two billion years.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Because Mars is small, cold, and lacks a magnetic field, it has retained only a sparse atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The surface air pressure of 0.6 kPa for Mars is only 0.6% of Earth's 101.3 kPa.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The planet has probably lost at least 80–85% of its original water supply to space.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] However, the planet has retained significant deposits of frozen water and carbon dioxide.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] If all of the frozen CO2 were to sublimate, the air pressure could climb to 30 kPa.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] This is comparable to the air pressure on the top of Mount Everest.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The composition of Earth's atmosphere is determined by the by-products of the life that it sustains.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Dry air (mixture of gases) from Earth's atmosphere contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and traces of hydrogen, helium, and other "noble" gases (by volume), but generally a variable amount of water vapor is also present, on average about 1% at sea level.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Earth's persistent magnetosphere acts as a shield against atmospheric scavenging by the solar wind, as it fends off the incoming plasma at a distance of about 10 Earth radii.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The low temperatures and higher escape velocities of the Solar System's giant planets—Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune—allow them more readily to retain gases with low molecular masses.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] These planets have reducing atmospheres of hydrogen and helium, with trace amounts of other elements and more complex compounds.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Unlike the terrestrial planets, the gas giants lack a well-defined surface.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Instead the atmosphere is maintained in hydrostatic equilibrium by intense pressure deep in the body.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The dynamic weather on these bodies only occurs in a relatively thin surface layer.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Two satellites of the outer planets possess significant atmospheres.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Titan, a moon of Saturn, and Triton, a moon of Neptune, have atmospheres mainly of nitrogen.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] When in the part of its orbit closest to the Sun, Pluto has an atmosphere of nitrogen and methane similar to Triton's, but these gases are frozen when it is farther from the Sun.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Other bodies within the Solar System have extremely thin atmospheres not in equilibrium.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] These include the Moon (sodium gas, noble gases, hydrogen), Mercury (sodium gas), Callisto (carbon dioxide and oxygen), Europa (oxygen), Io (sulfur dioxide), and Enceladus (water vapor).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Planetary objects around distant stars, known as exoplanets, span a more diverse range of physical properties than is found in the Solar System.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] These targets provide an opportunity to study atmospheres around a broad span of objects and conditions.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] However, observations of these targets requires much more sensitive instrumentation.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The methods used to analyze these remote atmospheres are transit spectroscopy, high-resolution Doppler spectroscopy, and direct imaging.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Transit spectroscopy uses the transit of an exoplanet across its host star to detect its atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] By comparing the radius at different wavelengths, the presence of specific components can be detected.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The first such detection was in 2002, when sodium was detected in the atmosphere of HD 209458b, a gas giant with a close orbit around a star in the constellation Pegasus.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Its atmosphere is heated to temperatures over 1,000 K, and is steadily escaping into space.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Hydrogen, oxygen, and carbon have been detected in the planet's inflated atmosphere by Hubble observations.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Since 2002, potassium has been detected in the atmosphere of XO-2Nb, and both sodium and potassium in HD 189733 b's atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Many of the discovered super earths have orbits close enough to their host star that their surfaces are expected to be magma oceans.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The secondary atmospheres of these lava planets most likely consist of materials that have been vaporized from the magma, such as sodium, potassium, oxygen, and silicon oxide.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] An atmosphere in hydrostatic equilibrium consists of a balance between the air pressure created by the motions of the molecules, and the restraining force of gravity that prevents the molecules from escaping.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The pressure decreases in altitude, producing a pressure-gradient force.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Atmospheric pressure is the force (per unit-area) perpendicular to a unit-area of planetary surface, as determined by the weight of the vertical column of atmospheric gases.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] In said atmospheric model, the atmospheric pressure, the weight of the mass of the gas, decreases at high altitude because of the diminishing mass of the gas above the point of barometric measurement.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Air pressure varies by place and time due to meteorological conditions and atmospheric waves.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Units of air pressure are based upon the standard atmosphere (atm), which is 101,325 Pa (equivalent to 760 Torr or 14.696 psi).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For an ideal gas atmosphere, the height at which the atmospheric pressure declines by a factor of *e* (the base of the natural logarithm) is called the scale height (*H*).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For an atmosphere of uniform temperature, the scale height is proportional to the atmospheric temperature and is inversely proportional to the product of the mean molecular mass of dry air, and the local acceleration of gravity at the point of barometric measurement.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The temperature of the atmosphere is determined by an energy budget, which balances the heating from the incoming solar energy against the heat radiated back into space.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The incoming energy is determined by the distance from the Sun, and the energy reflected back out by the planetary albedo.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] When a planet is in radiative equilibrium, it has a planetary equilibrium temperature.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] This differs from the global mean temperature, which may be warmer than the equilibrium temperature due to the atmospheric greenhouse effect.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For example, Venus has a surface temperature of almost 460 C compared to an equilibrium temperature of −40 C.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Planetary atmospheres are composed of layers with different properties, such as specific gaseous composition, temperature gradients, and pressure.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For Earth, Mars, and Venus, the lowest level of the atmosphere is the troposphere, where most of the planet's clouds and weather are found.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] This extends from the ground up to 65 km on Venus, 40 km on Mars, and 17 km on Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The troposphere contains the bulk of the atmosphere, possessing 80%–98% of the total atmospheric mass.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Temperature varies by altitude according to the lapse rate, as thermal energy from the ground is transported upward via convection.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Infrared radiation becomes trapped by molecules of gas and water vapor.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For the Earth, the next layer is the stratosphere, which is a region of temperature increasing with altitude, creating a temperature inversion.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] This region contains the UV-absorbing ozone layer, at an altitude between 15 km and 35 km, which is responsible for the temperature rise.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Energy transport in this region occurs through radiation processes.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Lacking an oxygenated atmosphere to generate a significant layer of ozone, neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Above the troposphere-stratosphere, the next layer of the atmosphere is termed the mesosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] In this region, the water vapor and carbon dioxide serves as a heat sink that radiates energy in the infrared.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] As a result, the temperature of the mesosphere decreases with altitude, reaching the coldest layer of the atmosphere at the top.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Both Venus and Mars have an altitude range in the mesosphere where the temperature is nearly isothermal; for Mars this is above 120 km, while for Venus it is between 63 and 75 km altitude.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] In the lower regions of the atmosphere, turbulent mixing causes the atmospheric constituents to be evenly distributed.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Above a transition layer called the homopause, molecular diffusion dominates.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] This results in diffuse separation of the constituents by atomic weight; that is, lower mass components diffuse upward leaving higher mass molecules near the bottom.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The homopause is at an altitude of 100–110 km for the Earth, 115–130 km for Mars, and 135–150 km for Venus.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Beyond the mesosphere is a region of the atmosphere called the thermosphere that absorbs X-rays and extreme UV from the Sun, causing temperature to rise with altitude.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The thermal properties of this layer vary daily and with solar activity cycles.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The atmospheric region from the ground through the thermosphere is referred to as the barosphere, since the barometric law holds throughout.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The outermost layer of a planetary atmosphere is termed the exosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Here, the air pressure is so low at this altitude that the distance travelled between molecule collisions, the mean free path, is greater than the atmospheric scale height.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] In this region, lower mass components with a thermal velocity exceeding the escape velocity can escape into space.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For the Earth, the exosphere is at an altitude of 500 km, while it is around 210 km for Venus and Mars.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] On Earth, the exosphere extends to roughly 10,000 km, where it interacts with the magnetosphere of Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] All three planets have an ionosphere, which is an ionized region of the upper atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The ionospheres for Mars and Venus are closer to the surface and are less dense than on the Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The density of the Earth's ionosphere is greater at short distances from the planetary surface in the daytime and decreases as the ionosphere rises at night-time, thereby allowing a greater range of radio frequencies to travel greater distances.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Gas giants are primarily composed of hydrogen and helium with traces of other elements, giving the planets a low bulk density.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Many of the molecules observed in the outer atmosphere are hydrides, and most of these (with the exception of H2O and H2S) are photochemically destroyed by solar UV in the stratosphere of Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] These compounds get re-created by thermo-chemical reactions within the hotter, lower regions of the atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Complex organic compounds are recycled back to methane by the highly reducing atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The high gravity of these planets combined with their distance from the Sun means that mass loss from their exospheres is negligible, so they form closed systems.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] A common feature of the gas giant planets are cloud layers that form where the combination of temperature and pressure are appropriate for condensing a particular volatile.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For Jupiter and Saturn, the outermost cloud layer consists of ice particles of ammonia (NH3), with an underlying layer of ammonium hydrosulfide (NH4SH), then a deep layer of water clouds (H2O).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For Uranus and Neptune, the top layer is a methane (CH4) layer of ice particles, followed by the same cloud layers as Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] One difference for Uranus and Neptune is that hydrogen sulfide (H2S) mixes at the same level as the condensed ammonia.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] These cloud layers are optically thick, absorbing light at all wavelengths.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The result is a shallower scale height for the outer atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] All four gas giants experience lightning activity in the water clouds, and this is generally much more powerful than terrestrial lightning.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Lightning has been observed on Jupiter, but has not been optically detected on Saturn, Uranus, or Neptune most likely because of their depth.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] All of the gas giants have internal heat sources and radiate more heat than they receive from the Sun.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Models for the interiors of Jupiter and Saturn suggest that at a certain depth the hydrogen undergoes a phase change to a metallic hydrogen fluid mixed with ice.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] There is possibly a diffuse or solid core of more massive elements.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For Uranus and Neptune, there is no metallic hydrogen; instead there are interior layers of ice, placing these worlds in the sub-category of ice giants.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] At sufficient depth, the ice may transition to a supercritical fluid.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Within the Solar System, gas giant planets formed beyond the frost line, where the temperature from the young Sun was low enough for volatiles to condense into solid grains.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] In some star systems, dynamic processes in the protoplanetary disk can cause a gas giant to migrate much closer to the central star, creating a hot Jupiter.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Through gravitational interaction, the orbit of the planet becomes circularized and it is tidally locked into a synchronous rotation with one side constantly facing the star.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The heated side becomes swollen, and high velocity winds distribute the thermal energy around the planet.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The atmosphere may eventually be stripped away by the star's gravity, leaving behind a super Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] At the upper mass extreme of gas giants is a class of objects known as brown dwarfs.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] There is no universal consensus on how to distinguish a brown dwarf from a gas giant, although a commonly used criteria is the ability to fuse deuterium at around 13 times the mass of Jupiter.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Once the initial deuterium burning phase of a brown dwarf is concluded, the internal store of heat gradually makes its way to the surface then is radiated away over time.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Convection occurs around the core, and possibly at the surface if the brown dwarf is receiving energy from a nearby star.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Radiative energy transfer occurs throughout the remainder of the brown dwarf.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Chemistry can occur throughout the atmosphere, which, depending on the chemical species, can change the opacity to radiative energy transfer.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] As with gas giants, in the cooler outer regions of a brown dwarf, some molecules can condense to form clouds.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The circulation of the atmosphere occurs due to thermal differences when convection becomes a more efficient transporter of heat than thermal radiation.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] On planets where the primary heat source is solar radiation, excess heat in the tropics is transported to higher latitudes.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] When a planet generates a significant amount of heat internally, such as is the case for Jupiter, convection in the atmosphere can transport thermal energy from the higher temperature interior up to the surface.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The thermally-driven meridional circulation of Earth, Mars, and Venus are dominated by the Hadley cell.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] This is created by rising air in the warmest region of the planet accompanied by descending air where it is cooler.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] However, there are significant differences in the circulation patterns between the three planets.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For Venus, the lower atmosphere of Venus has two symmetrical equator to near pole circulation cells, with a higher altitude sub-solar to anti-solar circulation cell.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] On Earth, Hadley cells exist on each side of the equator, but these vary seasonally due to the planet's obliquity.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Mars is similar to the Earth in this respect, but it displays greater seasonality due to its thinner atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] It has two Hadley cells during equinox, but a single cell at solstice.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The Earth has multiple counter-rotating convection cells, with the Hadley cell on either side of the equator, an intermediate Ferrel cell along the mid-latitudes, and polar cells at each pole.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The planet's rotation induces a Coriolis force that creates a curvature in the north-south convection flow.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] As air moves toward a pole, the latitudinal flow remains steady but the distance needed to encircle the planet grows shorter, creating a curved path along the surface.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] These flows create the prevailing winds along the planet's surface.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Near the equator, the air flow creates the trade winds which flow from east to west.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] At the mid-latitudes, the westerlies brings the air flow from the west in the United States and Europe.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Finally, the polar easterlies moves polar air from east to west.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Both Jupiter and Saturn display banded cloud formations.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] These are associated with alternating jets known as zonal flows that follow latitudinal lines.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The bands alternate in direction, with the equatorial jet moving eastward at 150 km/s on Jupiter and 300 km/s on Saturn.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] It remains unclear whether these flows occur in the shallow layers around the clouds, or extend much deeper into the atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Observations of Neptune show a similar zonal flow structure.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] This planet displays the largest range of differential rotation in the Solar System.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Surface gravity differs significantly among the planets.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For example, the large gravitational force of the giant planet Jupiter retains light gases such as hydrogen and helium that escape from objects with lower gravity.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Secondly, the distance from the Sun determines the energy available to heat atmospheric gas to the point where some fraction of its molecules' thermal motion exceed the planet's escape velocity, allowing those to escape a planet's gravitational grasp.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Thus, distant and cold Titan, Triton, and Pluto are able to retain components of their original atmospheres despite their relatively low gravities.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Since a collection of gas molecules may be moving at a wide range of velocities, there will always be some fast enough to produce a slow leakage of gas into space.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Lighter molecules move faster than heavier ones with the same thermal kinetic energy, and so gases of low molecular weight are lost more rapidly than those of high molecular weight.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] It is thought that Venus and Mars may have lost much of their water when, after being photodissociated into hydrogen and oxygen by solar ultraviolet radiation, the hydrogen escaped.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Earth's magnetic field helps to prevent this, as, normally, the solar wind would greatly enhance the escape of hydrogen.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] However, over the past 3 billion years Earth may have lost gases through the magnetic polar regions due to auroral activity, including a net 2% of its atmospheric oxygen.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The net effect, taking the most important escape processes into account, is that an intrinsic magnetic field does not protect a planet from atmospheric escape and that for some magnetizations the presence of a magnetic field works to increase the escape rate.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Planets around small M-type main-sequence stars may be particularly prone to atmospheric loss.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The star will spend an extended period as a superluminous pre-main-sequence star, then experience high levels of activity.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The strong stellar magnetic field will tend to reduce the size of planetary magnetospheres, leading to greater erosion from the stellar wind.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Planets around older M-type stars may become tidally locked in synchronous orbit, leading to the atmosphere being permanently frozen on the dark face.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Other mechanisms that can cause atmosphere depletion are solar wind-induced sputtering, impact erosion, weathering, and sequestration—sometimes referred to as "freezing out"—into the regolith and polar caps.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] An extreme example of the latter is a comet, which is a small body that forms beyond the frost line in the protoplanetary disk.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] These objects contain many types of frozen volatiles, including water, carbon dioxide, ammonia, methane, and formaldehyde.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] As these objects approach the Sun, the thermal radiation causes the volatiles to sublimate, creating a diffuse, dusty atmosphere around the comet; the coma.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] However, the gravitational potential of the comet is insufficient to retain this atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] The Solar System contains a large number of bodies that are now practically airless, such as Mercury and the Moon.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] These objects have only an exosphere layer with particles that are essentially collisionless.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] In this environment, atoms and molecules are released from the surface by various means, including particle sputtering and micrometeorite impact.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] When the release velocity of these particles exceed the escape velocity, they are lost to space.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Higher mass particles have a greater chance to be returned to the surface, which creates a chemical alteration of the surface over time.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] On a terrestrial planet, the part of the atmosphere that directly interacts with the ground is known as the planetary boundary layer.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Atmospheres have dramatic effects on the surfaces of rocky bodies.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Wind erosion is a significant factor in shaping the terrain of rocky planets with atmospheres, and over time can erase the effects of both craters and volcanoes.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] In addition, since liquids cannot exist without pressure, an atmosphere allows liquid to be present at the surface, resulting in lakes, rivers and oceans.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Earth and Titan are known to have liquids at their surface and terrain on the planet Mars suggests that it had liquid on its surface in the past.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Objects that have no atmosphere, or that have only an exosphere, have terrain that is covered in craters.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Without an atmosphere, the planet has no protection from meteoroids, and all of them collide with the surface as meteorites and create craters.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For planets with a significant atmosphere, most meteoroids burn up as meteors before hitting a planet's surface.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] When meteoroids do impact, the effects are often erased by the action of wind.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] From the perspective of a planetary geologist, the atmosphere acts to shape a planetary surface.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Wind picks up dust and other particles which, when they collide with the terrain, erode the relief and leave deposits (eolian processes).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Frost and precipitations, which depend on the atmospheric composition, also influence the relief.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Climate changes can influence a planet's geological history.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] Conversely, studying the surface of the Earth leads to an understanding of the atmosphere and climate of other planets.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For a meteorologist, the composition of the Earth's atmosphere is a factor affecting the climate and its variations.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] For a biologist or paleontologist, the Earth's atmospheric composition is closely dependent on the appearance of life and its evolution.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmosphere] In astrobiology, the composition of an exoplanet's atmosphere is closely intertwined with the possibility of extraterrestrial life.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] In most circumstances, atmospheric pressure is closely approximated by the hydrostatic pressure caused by the weight of air above the measurement point.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] As elevation increases, there is less overlying atmospheric mass, so atmospheric pressure decreases with increasing elevation.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Because the atmosphere is thin relative to the Earth's radius – especially the dense atmospheric layer at low altitudes – the Earth's gravitational acceleration as a function of altitude can be approximated as constant and contributes little to this fall-off.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure measures force per unit area, with SI units of pascals (1 pascal = 1 newton per square meter, 1 N/m2).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] A column of air with a cross-sectional area of 1 in2 would have a weight of about 14.7 lbf, resulting in a pressure of 14.7 lbf/in2.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure is caused by the gravitational attraction of the planet on the atmospheric gases above the surface and is a function of the mass of the planet, the radius of the surface, and the amount and composition of the gases and their vertical distribution in the atmosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] It is modified by the planetary rotation and local effects such as wind velocity, density variations due to temperature and variations in composition.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The *mean sea-level pressure* (MSLP) is the atmospheric pressure at mean sea level.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] This is the atmospheric pressure normally given in weather reports via meteorologists on radio, television, and newspapers or on the Internet.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The *altimeter setting* in aviation is an atmospheric pressure adjustment.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] In aviation weather reports (METAR), QNH is transmitted around the world in hectopascals or millibars (1 hectopascal = 1 millibar).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] In the United States, Canada, and Japan altimeter setting is reported in inches of mercury (to two decimal places).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The United States and Canada also report *sea-level pressure* SLP, which is adjusted to sea level by a different method, in the remarks section, not in the internationally transmitted part of the code, in hectopascals or millibars.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] However, in Canada's public weather reports, sea level pressure is instead reported in kilopascals.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] In the US weather code remarks, three digits are all that are transmitted; decimal points and the one or two most significant digits are omitted: 1,013.2 hPa (14.695 psi) is transmitted as 132; 1,000 hPa (100 kPa) is transmitted as 000; 998.7 hPa is transmitted as 987; etc.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] A system transmitting the last three digits transmits the same code (800) for 1080.0 hPa as for 980.0 hPa.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The highest *sea-level pressure* on Earth occurs in Siberia, where the Siberian High often attains a *sea-level pressure* above 1,050 hPa (15.2 psi; 31 inHg), with record highs close to 1,085 hPa (15.74 psi; 32.0 inHg).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The lowest measurable *sea-level pressure* is found at the centres of tropical cyclones and tornadoes, with a record low of 870 hPa (12.6 psi; 26 inHg).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] For numerical reasons, atmospheric models such as general circulation models (GCMs) usually predict the nondimensional *logarithm of surface pressure*.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The average value of surface pressure on Earth is 985 hPa.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] This is in contrast to mean sea-level pressure, which involves the extrapolation of pressure to sea level for locations above or below sea level.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The average pressure at mean sea level (MSL) in the International Standard Atmosphere (ISA) is 1,013.25 hPa, or 1 atmosphere (atm), or 29.92 inches of mercury.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure (P), mass (m), and acceleration due to gravity (g) are related by P = F/A = (m*g)/A, where A is the surface area.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure is thus proportional to the weight per unit area of the atmospheric mass above that location.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure on Earth varies with the altitude of the surface, so air pressure on mountains is usually lower than air pressure at sea level.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure varies smoothly from the Earth's surface to the top of the mesosphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Although the pressure changes with the weather, NASA has averaged the conditions for all parts of the earth year-round.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] As altitude increases, atmospheric pressure decreases.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] One can calculate the atmospheric pressure at a given altitude.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Temperature and humidity also affect the atmospheric pressure.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure is proportional to temperature and inversely related to humidity, and both of these are necessary to compute an accurate figure.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The graph on the rightabove was developed for a temperature of 15 °C and a relative humidity of 0%.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] At low altitudes above sea level, the pressure decreases by about 1.2 kPa (12 hPa) for every 100 meters.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure varies widely on Earth, and differences in pressure are important in studying weather and climate.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Some variations in pressure are very regular.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] One important source of variation is atmospheric tides.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric tides are strongest in tropical zones, with an amplitude of a few hectopascals, and almost zero in polar areas.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Tropical tidal variations in pressure consist principally of two superimposed harmonics – a circadian (24 h) cycle and a semi-circadian (12 h) cycle.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded on Earth above 750 meters was 1,084.8 hPa (32.03 inHg; 1.0706 atm), measured in Tosontsengel, Mongolia on 19 December 2001.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded below 750 meters was at Agata, in Evenk Autonomous Okrug, Russia (66°53' N, 93°28' E, elevation: 261 m, 856 ft), on 31 December 1968 of 1,083.8 hPa (32.005 inHg).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The Dead Sea, the lowest sea surface on Earth, at 430 metres (1,410 ft) below sea level, has a correspondingly high typical atmospheric pressure of 1,065 hPa.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] A below-sea-level surface pressure record of 1,081.8 hPa (31.95 inHg; 1.0677 atm) was set on 21 February 1961.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The lowest non-tornadic atmospheric pressure ever measured was 870 hPa (26 inHg; 0.86 atm), set on 12 October 1979, during Typhoon Tip in the western Pacific Ocean.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The measurement was based on an instrumental observation made from a reconnaissance aircraft.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] One atmosphere (101.325 kPa or 14.7 psi) is also the pressure caused by the weight of a column of freshwater of approximately 10.3 m (33.8 ft).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Thus, a diver 10.3 m under water experiences a pressure of about 2 atmospheres (1 atm of air plus 1 atm of water).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Conversely, 10.3 m is the maximum height to which water can be raised using suction under standard atmospheric conditions.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Low pressures, such as natural gas lines, are sometimes specified in inches of water, typically written as *w.c.* (water column) gauge or *w.g.* (inches water) gauge.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] A typical gas-using residential appliance in the US is rated for a maximum of 1⁄2 psi (3.4 kPa; 34 mbar), which is approximately 14 w.g.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Similar metric units with a wide variety of names and notation based on millimeters, centimeters or meters are now less commonly used.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Pure water boils at 100 °C (212 °F) at Earth's standard atmospheric pressure.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] The boiling point is the temperature at which the vapour pressure is equal to the atmospheric pressure around the liquid.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Because of this, the boiling point of liquids is lower at lower pressure and higher at higher pressure.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Cooking at high elevations, therefore, requires adjustments to recipes or pressure cooking.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] A rough approximation of elevation can be obtained by measuring the temperature at which water boils; in the mid-19th century, this method was used by explorers.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] Conversely, if one wishes to evaporate a liquid at a lower temperature, for example in distillation, the atmospheric pressure may be lowered by using a vacuum pump, as in a rotary evaporator.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] An important application of the knowledge that atmospheric pressure varies directly with altitude was in determining the height of hills and mountains, thanks to reliable pressure measurement devices.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] In 1774, Nevil Maskelyne was confirming Newton's theory of gravitation at and on Schiehallion mountain in Scotland, and he needed to measure elevations on the mountain's sides accurately.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] This event is known as the Schiehallion experiment.
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] William Roy, using barometric pressure, was able to confirm Maskelyne's height determinations; the agreement was within one meter (3.28 feet).
[src:chandler-wobble/atmospheric-pressure] This method became and continues to be useful for survey work and map making.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In astronomy, **axial precession** is a gravity-induced, slow, and continuous change in the orientation of an astronomical body's rotational axis.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In the absence of precession, the astronomical body's orbit would show axial parallelism.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In particular, Earth's axial precession is the gradual shift in the orientation of Earth's axis of rotation.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] It has a cycle of approximately 26,000 years, tracing out a double cone with a half-aperture of about 23.4°, an angle known as the obliquity of the ecliptic.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This is similar to the precession of a spinning top.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The term "precession" typically refers only to this largest part of the motion; other changes in the alignment of Earth's axis—nutation and polar motion—are much smaller in magnitude.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Earth's precession was historically called the **precession of the equinoxes**, because the equinoxes moved westward along the ecliptic relative to the fixed stars, opposite to the yearly motion of the Sun along the ecliptic.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Historically, the discovery of the precession of the equinoxes is usually attributed in the West to the 2nd-century-BC astronomer Hipparchus.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Their combination was named **general precession**, instead of precession of the equinoxes.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Lunisolar precession is caused by the gravitational forces of the Moon and Sun on Earth's equatorial bulge, causing Earth's axis to move with respect to inertial space.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Planetary precession (an advance) is due to the small angle between the gravitational force of the other planets on Earth and its orbital plane (the ecliptic), causing the plane of the ecliptic to shift slightly relative to inertial space.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Lunisolar precession is about 500 times greater than planetary precession.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Many references to the old terms exist in publications predating the change.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The term "precession" as it is used in astronomy generally describes the observed but exceedingly slow 26,000 year changing location of the place where the Sun appears against the background stars when it travels northward across the equator, at the moment of the March equinox.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The stars oppositely seem to be moving retrograde across the sky, relative to the false-perspective that the stars move, rather than the equinox locations moving.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In physics the term "precession" is generally used slightly differently to instead describe the analogous mechanical process of spinning tops shifting their orientation to their surroundings when tipped slightly while spinning.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The term "precession" is derived from the Latin *praecedere* ("to precede, to come before, to be earlier").
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] As viewed from Earth, the stars are seen to drift slightly faster than one full revolution across the sky from east to west, at about 15 degrees per hour, due to the Earth's actual diurnal motion in the opposite direction.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The stars also rotate around the Earth's axis even more slowly, once every year (at about 1 degree per day), which is a mirror reflection of the Earth's orbital motion around the Sun.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] At the same time the stars can be observed to move yet again more slowly in the same direction as their annual circuit of the Earth's polar axis, very slightly faster than their normal yearly motion.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] That later rate is approximately 50 arcseconds per year – 1 degree every 72 years or one full rotation about every 26,000 years – a phenomenon known as the "precession of the equinoxes".
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In describing the motion they see, astronomers generally have shortened the term to simply *"precession"*.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Physicists also use the term "precession" to describe the *cause* of the motion, which has led to some confusion between the phenomenon observed in the sky and the imbalance of torques that causes tops to wobble.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The issue is further obfuscated by the fact that modern astronomers are almost entirely physicists, and mix the astronomical and physical vocabularies, whose fine distinctions that might be more easily understood if kept separate.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The precession of the Earth's axis has a number of observable effects.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] First, the positions of the south and north celestial poles appear to move in circles against the space-fixed backdrop of stars, completing one circuit in approximately 26,000 years.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Thus, while today the star Polaris lies approximately at the north celestial pole, this will change over time, and other stars will become the "north star".
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In approximately 3,200 years, the star Gamma Cephei in the Cepheus constellation will succeed Polaris for this position.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The south celestial pole currently lacks a bright star to mark its position, but over time precession also will cause bright stars to become South Stars.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] As the celestial poles shift, there is a corresponding gradual shift in the apparent orientation of the whole star field, as viewed from a particular position on Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Secondly, the position of the Earth in its orbit around the Sun at the solstices, equinoxes, or other time defined relative to the seasons, slowly changes.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For example, suppose that the Earth's orbital position is marked at the summer solstice, when the Earth's axial tilt is pointing most nearly toward the Sun.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] One full orbit later, when the Sun has returned to the same apparent position relative to the background stars, the Earth's axial tilt is not now directly toward the Sun: because of the effects of precession, it is a little way "beyond" this.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In other words, the solstice occurred a little *earlier* in the orbit.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Thus, the tropical year, measuring the cycle of seasons (for example, the time from solstice to solstice, or equinox to equinox), is about 20 minutes shorter than the sidereal year, which is measured by the Sun's apparent position relative to the stars.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] After about 26 000 years the difference amounts to a full year, so the positions of the seasons relative to the orbit are "back where they started".
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] (Other effects also slowly change the shape and orientation of the Earth's orbit, and these, in combination with precession, create various cycles of differing periods; see also Milankovitch cycles.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For identical reasons, the apparent position of the Sun relative to the backdrop of the stars at some seasonally fixed time slowly regresses a full 360° through all twelve traditional constellations of the zodiac, at the rate of about 50.3 seconds of arc per year, or 1 degree every 71.6 years.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] At present, the rate of precession corresponds to a period of 25,772 years, so a tropical year is shorter than a sidereal year by 1,224.5 seconds (20 min 24.5 sec ≈ (365.24219 × 86400) / 25772).
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The rate itself varies somewhat with time (see Values below), so one cannot say that in exactly 25,772 years the Earth's axis will be back to where it is now.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For further details, see Changing pole stars and Polar shift and equinoxes shift, below.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The discovery of precession usually is attributed to Hipparchus (190–120 BC) of Rhodes or Nicaea, a Greek astronomer.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] According to Ptolemy's *Almagest*, Hipparchus measured the longitude of Spica and other bright stars.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Comparing his measurements with data from his predecessors, Timocharis (320–260 BC) and Aristillus (~280 BC), he concluded that Spica had moved 2° relative to the autumnal equinox.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] He also compared the lengths of the tropical year (the time it takes the Sun to return to an equinox) and the sidereal year (the time it takes the Sun to return to a fixed star), and found a slight discrepancy.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Hipparchus concluded that the equinoxes were moving ("precessing") through the zodiac, and that the rate of precession was not less than 1° in a century, in other words, completing a full cycle in no more than 36,000 years.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Virtually all of the writings of Hipparchus are lost, including his work on precession.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] They are mentioned by Ptolemy, who explains precession as the rotation of the celestial sphere around a motionless Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] It is reasonable to presume that Hipparchus, like Ptolemy, thought of precession in geocentric terms as a motion of the heavens, rather than of the Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The first astronomer known to have continued Hipparchus's work on precession is Ptolemy in the second century AD.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Ptolemy measured the longitudes of Regulus, Spica, and other bright stars with a variation of Hipparchus's lunar method that did not require eclipses.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Before sunset, he measured the longitudinal arc separating the Moon from the Sun.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Then, after sunset, he measured the arc from the Moon to the star.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] He used Hipparchus's model to calculate the Sun's longitude, and made corrections for the Moon's motion and its parallax.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Ptolemy compared his own observations with those made by Hipparchus, Menelaus of Alexandria, Timocharis, and Agrippa.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] He found that between Hipparchus's time and his own (roughly 265 years) the stars had moved 2°40', or 1° in 100 years (36" per year; the rate accepted today is about 50" per year or 1° in 72 years).
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Ptolemy stated that he made his own observations at the beginning of the reign of the emperor Antoninus Pius and he said Hipparchus had made his in the 50th year of the third Callippic cycle.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Ptolemy also confirmed that precession affected all fixed stars, not just those near the ecliptic, with the same period of 36,000 years.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Most ancient authors did not mention precession and, perhaps, did not know of it.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For instance, Proclus rejected precession, while Theon of Alexandria, a commentator on Ptolemy in the fourth century, accepted Ptolemy's explanation.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] "According to certain opinions ancient astrologers believe that from a certain epoch the solstitial signs have a motion of 8° in the order of the signs, after which they go back the same amount. ..." (Dreyer 1958, p.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Instead of proceeding through the entire sequence of the zodiac, the equinoxes "trepidated" back and forth over an arc of 8°.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The theory of trepidation is presented by Theon as an alternative to precession.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Various assertions have been made that other cultures discovered precession independently of Hipparchus.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] According to Al-Battani, the Chaldean astronomers had distinguished the tropical and sidereal year so that by approximately 330 BC, they would have been in a position to describe precession, if inaccurately, but such claims generally are regarded as unsupported.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Archaeologist Susan Milbrath has speculated that the Mesoamerican Long Count calendar of "30,000 years involving the Pleiades...may have been an effort to calculate the precession of the equinox." This view is held by few other professional scholars of Maya civilization.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Similarly, it is claimed the precession of the equinoxes was known in Ancient Egypt, prior to the time of Hipparchus (the Ptolemaic period).
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Ancient Egyptians kept accurate calendars and recorded dates on temple walls, so it would be a simple matter for them to plot the "rough" precession rate.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The Dendera Zodiac, a star-map inside the Hathor temple at Dendera, allegedly records the precession of the equinoxes.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In any case, if the ancient Egyptians knew of precession, their knowledge is not recorded as such in any of their surviving astronomical texts.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Michael Rice, a popular writer on Ancient Egypt, has written that Ancient Egyptians must have observed the precession, and suggested that this awareness had profound effects on their culture.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Rice noted that Egyptians re-oriented temples in response to precession of associated stars.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Before 1200, India had two theories of trepidation, one with a rate and another without a rate, and several related models of precession.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Each had minor changes or corrections by various commentators.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The dominant of the three was the trepidation described by the most respected Indian astronomical treatise, the *Surya Siddhanta* (3:9–12), composed c.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] 400 but revised during the next few centuries.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] It used a sidereal epoch, or ayanamsa, that is still used by all Indian calendars, varying over the ecliptic longitude of 19°11′ to 23°51′, depending on the group consulted.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This epoch causes the roughly 30 Indian calendar years to begin 23–28 days after the modern March equinox.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The March equinox of the *Surya Siddhanta* librated 27° in both directions from the sidereal epoch.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Thus the equinox moved 54° in one direction and then back 54° in the other direction.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This cycle took 7200 years to complete at a rate of 54″/year.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The equinox coincided with the epoch at the beginning of the *Kali Yuga* in −3101 and again 3,600 years later in 499.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The direction changed from prograde to retrograde midway between these years at −1301 when it reached its maximum deviation of 27°, and would have remained retrograde, the same direction as modern precession, for 3600 years until 2299.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Another trepidation was described by Varāhamihira (c.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] His trepidation consisted of an arc of 46°40′ in one direction and a return to the starting point.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Half of this arc, 23°20′, was identified with the Sun's maximum declination on either side of the equator at the solstices.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] But no period was specified, thus no annual rate can be ascertained.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] They probably deviated from an even 200,000 revolutions to make the accumulated precession zero near 500.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Yu Xi (fourth century AD) was the first Chinese astronomer to mention precession.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] He estimated the rate of precession as 1° in 50 years.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In medieval Islamic astronomy, precession was known based on Ptolemy's *Almagest*, and by observations that refined the value.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Al-Battani, in his work *Zij Al-Sabi*, mentions Hipparchus's calculation of precession, and Ptolemy's value of 1 degree per 100 solar years, says that he measured precession and found it to be one degree per 66 solar years.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Subsequently, Al-Sufi, in his *Book of Fixed Stars*, mentions the same values that Ptolemy's value for precession is 1 degree per 100 solar years.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] He then quotes a different value from *Zij Al Mumtahan*, which was done during Al-Ma'mun's reign, of 1 degree for every 66 solar years.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] He also quotes the aforementioned *Zij Al-Sabi* of Al-Battani as adjusting coordinates for stars by 11 degrees and 10 minutes of arc to account for the difference between Al-Battani's time and Ptolemy's.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Later, the *Zij-i Ilkhani*, compiled at the Maragheh observatory, sets the precession of the equinoxes at 51 arc seconds per annum, which is very close to the modern value of 50.2 arc seconds.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In the Middle Ages, Islamic and Latin Christian astronomers treated "trepidation" as a motion of the fixed stars to be *added to* precession.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This theory is commonly attributed to the Arab astronomer Thabit ibn Qurra, but the attribution has been contested in modern times.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Nicolaus Copernicus published a different account of trepidation in *De revolutionibus orbium coelestium* (1543).
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This work makes the first definite reference to precession as the result of a motion of the Earth's axis.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Copernicus characterized precession as the third motion of the Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Over a century later, Isaac Newton in *Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica* (1687) explained precession as a consequence of gravitation.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] However, Newton's original precession equations did not work, and were revised considerably by Jean le Rond d'Alembert and subsequent scientists.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Hipparchus gave an account of his discovery in *On the Displacement of the Solsticial and Equinoctial Points* (described in *Almagest* III.1 and VII.2).
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] He measured the ecliptic longitude of the star Spica during lunar eclipses and found that it was about 6° west of the autumnal equinox.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] By comparing his own measurements with those of Timocharis of Alexandria (a contemporary of Euclid, who worked with Aristillus early in the 3rd century BC), he found that Spica's longitude had decreased by about 2° in the meantime (exact years are not mentioned in *Almagest*).
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Also in VII.2, Ptolemy gives more precise observations of two stars, including Spica, and concludes that in each case a 2° 40' change occurred between 128 BC and AD 139.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Hence, 1° per century or one full cycle in 36,000 years, that is, the precessional period of Hipparchus as reported by Ptolemy; cf. page 328 in Toomer's translation of Almagest, 1998 edition.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] He also noticed this motion in other stars.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] He speculated that only the stars near the zodiac shifted over time.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Ptolemy called this his "first hypothesis" (*Almagest* VII.1), but did not report any later hypothesis Hipparchus might have devised.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Hipparchus apparently limited his speculations, because he had only a few older observations, which were not very reliable.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Because the equinoctial points are not marked in the sky, Hipparchus needed the Moon as a reference point; he used a lunar eclipse to measure the position of a star.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Hipparchus already had developed a way to calculate the longitude of the Sun at any moment.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] A lunar eclipse happens during Full moon, when the Moon is at opposition, precisely 180° from the Sun.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Hipparchus is thought to have measured the longitudinal arc separating Spica from the Moon.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] To this value, he added the calculated longitude of the Sun, plus 180° for the longitude of the Moon.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] He did the same procedure with Timocharis' data.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Observations such as these eclipses, incidentally, are the main source of data about when Hipparchus worked, since other biographical information about him is minimal.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The lunar eclipses he observed, for instance, took place on 21 April 146 BC, and 21 March 135 BC.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Hipparchus also studied precession in *On the Length of the Year*.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Two kinds of year are relevant to understanding his work.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The tropical year is the length of time that the Sun, as viewed from the Earth, takes to return to the same position along the ecliptic (its path among the stars on the celestial sphere).
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The sidereal year is the length of time that the Sun takes to return to the same position with respect to the stars of the celestial sphere.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Precession causes the stars to change their longitude slightly each year, so the sidereal year is longer than the tropical year.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Using observations of the equinoxes and solstices, Hipparchus found that the length of the tropical year was 365+1/4−1/300 days, or 365.24667 days (Evans 1998, p.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Comparing this with the length of the sidereal year, he calculated that the rate of precession was not less than 1° in a century.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] From this information, it is possible to calculate that his value for the sidereal year was 365+1/4+1/144 days.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] By giving a minimum rate, he may have been allowing for errors in observation.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] To approximate his tropical year, Hipparchus created his own lunisolar calendar by modifying those of Meton and Callippus in *On Intercalary Months and Days* (now lost), as described by Ptolemy in the *Almagest* III.1.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The Babylonian calendar used a cycle of 235 lunar months in 19 years since 499 BC (with only three exceptions before 380 BC), but it did not use a specified number of days.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The Metonic cycle (432 BC) assigned 6,940 days to these 19 years producing an average year of 365+1/4+1/76 or 365.26316 days.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The Callippic cycle (330 BC) dropped one day from four Metonic cycles (76 years) for an average year of 365+1/4 or 365.25 days.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Hipparchus dropped one more day from four Callippic cycles (304 years), creating the Hipparchic cycle with an average year of 365+1/4−1/304 or 365.24671 days, which was close to his tropical year of 365+1/4−1/300 or 365.24667 days.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Hipparchus's mathematical signatures are found in the Antikythera Mechanism, an ancient astronomical computer of the second century BC.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Study of the Antikythera Mechanism showed that the ancients used very accurate calendars based on all the aspects of solar and lunar motion in the sky.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In fact, the Lunar Mechanism which is part of the Antikythera Mechanism depicts the motion of the Moon and its phase, for a given time, using a train of four gears with a pin and slot device which gives a variable lunar velocity that is very close to Kepler's second law.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] That is, it takes into account the fast motion of the Moon at perigee and slower motion at apogee.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] A consequence of the precession is a changing pole star.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Currently Polaris is extremely well suited to mark the position of the north celestial pole, as Polaris is a moderately bright star with a visual magnitude of 2.1 (variable), and is located about one degree from the pole, with no stars of similar brightness too close.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The previous pole star was Kochab (Beta Ursae Minoris, β UMi, β Ursae Minoris), the brightest star in the bowl of the "Little Dipper", located 16 degrees from Polaris.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] It held that role from 1500 BC to AD 500.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] It was not quite as accurate in its day as Polaris is today.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Today, Kochab and its neighbor Pherkad are referred to as the "Guardians of the Pole" (meaning Polaris).
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] On the other hand, Thuban in the constellation Draco, which was the pole star in 3000 BC, is much less conspicuous at magnitude 3.67 (one-fifth as bright as Polaris); today it is invisible in light-polluted urban skies.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] When Polaris becomes the north star again around 27,800, it will then be farther away from the pole than it is now due to its proper motion, while in 23,600 BC it came closer to the pole.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] It is more difficult to find the south celestial pole in the sky at this moment, as that area is a particularly bland portion of the sky.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The nominal south pole star is Sigma Octantis, which with magnitude 5.5 is barely visible to the naked eye even under ideal conditions.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] That will change from the 80th to the 90th centuries, however, when the south celestial pole travels through the False Cross.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This situation also is seen on a star map.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The orientation of the south pole is moving toward the Southern Cross constellation.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For the last 2,000 years or so, the Southern Cross has pointed to the south celestial pole.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] As a consequence, the constellation is difficult to view from subtropical northern latitudes, unlike in the time of the ancient Greeks.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The Southern Cross can be viewed from as far north as Miami (about 25° N), but only during the winter/early spring.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The images at right attempt to explain the relation between the precession of the Earth's axis and the shift in the equinoxes.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] These images show the position of the Earth's axis on the *celestial sphere*, a fictitious sphere which places the stars according to their position as seen from Earth, regardless of their actual distance.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The first image shows the celestial sphere from the outside, with the constellations in mirror image.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The second image shows the perspective of a near-Earth position as seen through a very wide angle lens (from which the apparent distortion arises).
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The rotation axis of the Earth describes, over a period of 25,700 years, a small blue circle among the stars near the top of the diagram, centered on the ecliptic north pole (the blue letter **E**) and with an angular radius of about 23.4°, an angle known as the *obliquity of the ecliptic*.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The direction of precession is opposite to the daily rotation of the Earth on its axis.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The brown axis was the Earth's rotation axis 5,000 years ago, when it pointed to the star Thuban.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The yellow axis, pointing to Polaris, marks the axis now.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] When the axis *precesses* from one orientation to another, the equatorial plane of the Earth (indicated by the circular grid around the equator) moves.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The celestial equator is just the Earth's equator projected onto the celestial sphere, so it moves as the Earth's equatorial plane moves, and the intersection with the ecliptic moves with it.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The positions of the poles and equator *on Earth* do not change, only the orientation of the Earth against the fixed stars.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] As seen from the brown grid, 5,000 years ago, the March equinox was close to the star Aldebaran in Taurus.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Now, as seen from the yellow grid, it has shifted (indicated by the red arrow) to somewhere in the constellation of Pisces.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The precession of the equinoxes is caused by the gravitational forces of the Sun and the Moon, and to a lesser extent other bodies, on the Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Axial precession is similar to the precession of a spinning top.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In both cases, the applied force is due to gravity.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For a spinning top, this force tends to be almost parallel to the rotation axis initially and increases as the top slows down.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For a gyroscope on a stand it can approach 90 degrees.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For the Earth, however, the applied forces of the Sun and the Moon are closer to perpendicular to the axis of rotation.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The Earth is not a perfect sphere but an oblate spheroid, with an equatorial diameter about 43 kilometers larger than its polar diameter.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Because of the Earth's axial tilt, during most of the year the half of this bulge that is closest to the Sun is off-center, either to the north or to the south, and the far half is off-center on the opposite side.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The gravitational pull on the closer half is stronger, since gravity decreases with the square of distance, so this creates a small torque on the Earth as the Sun pulls harder on one side of the Earth than the other.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The axis of this torque is roughly perpendicular to the axis of the Earth's rotation so the axis of rotation precesses.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] If the Earth were a perfect sphere, there would be no precession.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This average torque is perpendicular to the direction in which the rotation axis is tilted away from the ecliptic pole, so that it does not change the axial tilt itself.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The magnitude of the torque from the Sun (or the Moon) varies with the angle between the Earth's spin axis direction and that of the gravitational attraction.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] It approaches zero when they are perpendicular.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For example, this happens at the equinoxes in the case of the interaction with the Sun.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This can be seen to be since the near and far points are aligned with the gravitational attraction, so there is no torque due to the difference in gravitational attraction.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Although the above explanation involved the Sun, the same explanation holds true for any object moving around the Earth, along or close to the ecliptic, notably, the Moon.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The combined action of the Sun and the Moon is called the lunisolar precession.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In addition to the steady progressive motion (resulting in a full circle in about 25,700 years) the Sun and Moon also cause small periodic variations, due to their changing positions.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] These oscillations, in both precessional speed and axial tilt, are known as the nutation.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The most important term has a period of 18.6 years and an amplitude of 9.2 arcseconds.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In addition to lunisolar precession, the actions of the other planets of the Solar System cause the whole ecliptic to rotate slowly around an axis which has an ecliptic longitude of about 174° measured on the instantaneous ecliptic.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This so-called planetary precession shift amounts to a rotation of the ecliptic plane of 0.47 seconds of arc per year (more than a hundred times smaller than lunisolar precession).
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The sum of the two precessions is known as the general precession.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This gives the paradoxical notion of a force acting away from the satellite but in reality it is simply a lesser force toward that body due to the gradient in the gravitational field.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For precession, this tidal force can be grouped into two forces which only act on the equatorial bulge outside of a mean spherical radius.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This couple can be decomposed into two pairs of components, one pair parallel to Earth's equatorial plane toward and away from the perturbing body which cancel each other out, and another pair parallel to Earth's rotational axis, both toward the ecliptic plane.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The value of the three sinusoidal terms in the direction of **x** (sin*δ* cos*δ* sin*α*) for the Sun is a sine squared waveform varying from zero at the equinoxes (0°, 180°) to 0.36495 at the solstices (90°, 270°).
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Both solar waveforms have about the same peak-to-peak amplitude and the same period, half of a revolution or half of a year.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The value in the direction of **z** is zero.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The average torque of the sine wave in the direction of **y** is zero for the Sun or Moon, so this component of the torque does not affect precession.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] where *ω* is Earth's angular velocity and *Cω* is Earth's angular momentum.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] where *i* is the angle between the plane of the Moon's orbit and the ecliptic plane.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In these two equations, the Sun's parameters are within square brackets labeled S, the Moon's parameters are within square brackets labeled L, and the Earth's parameters are within square brackets labeled E.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The term $\left(1-1.5\sin ^{2}i\right)$ accounts for the inclination of the Moon's orbit relative to the ecliptic.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The term (*C* − *A*)/*C* is Earth's dynamical ellipticity or flattening, which is adjusted to the observed precession because Earth's internal structure is not known with sufficient detail.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The solar equation is a good representation of precession due to the Sun because Earth's orbit is close to an ellipse, being only slightly perturbed by the other planets.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The lunar equation is not as good a representation of precession due to the Moon because the Moon's orbit is greatly distorted by the Sun and neither the radius nor the eccentricity is constant over the year.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Jay Henry Lieske developed an updated theory in 1976, where *p* equals 5,029.0966 arcseconds (or 1.3969713 degrees) per Julian century.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The precession rate is not a constant, but is (at the moment) slowly increasing over time, as indicated by the linear (and higher order) terms in *T*.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In any case it must be stressed that this formula is only valid over a *limited time period*.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] It is a polynomial expression centred on the J2000 datum, empirically fitted to observational data, not on a deterministic model of the Solar System.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] It is clear that if *T* gets large enough (far in the future or far in the past), the *T*² term will dominate and *p* will go to very large values.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In reality, more elaborate calculations on the numerical model of the Solar System show that the precessional rate has a period of about 41,000 years, the same as the obliquity of the ecliptic.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Theoretical models may calculate the constants (coefficients) corresponding to the higher powers of *T*, but since it is impossible for a polynomial to match a periodic function over all numbers, the difference in all such approximations will grow without bound as *T* increases.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Sufficient accuracy can be obtained over a limited time span by fitting a high enough order polynomial to observation data, rather than a necessarily imperfect dynamic numerical model.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For present flight trajectory calculations of artificial satellites and spacecraft, the polynomial method gives better accuracy.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] In that respect, the International Astronomical Union has chosen the best-developed available theory.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For up to a few centuries into the past and future, none of the formulas used diverge very much.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For up to a few thousand years in the past and the future, most agree to some accuracy.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] For eras farther out, discrepancies become too large – the exact rate and period of precession may not be computed using these polynomials even for a single whole precession period.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The precession of Earth's axis is a very slow effect, but at the level of accuracy at which astronomers work, it does need to be taken into account on a daily basis.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Although the precession and the tilt of Earth's axis (the obliquity of the ecliptic) are calculated from the same theory and are thus related one to the other, the two movements act independently of each other, moving in opposite directions.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Precession rate exhibits a secular decrease due to tidal dissipation from 59"/a to 45"/a (a = annus = Julian year) during the 500 million year period centered on the present.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This gives an average cycle length now of 25,676 years.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Precession will be greater than *p*+ by the small amount of +0.135052"/a between +30 Ma and +130 Ma.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] The jump to this excess over *p*+ will occur in only 20 Ma beginning now because the secular decrease in precession is beginning to cross a resonance in Earth's orbit caused by the other planets.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] This will be associated with wild swings in the obliquity of the ecliptic as well.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Ward, however, used the abnormally large modern value for tidal dissipation.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] Using the 620-million year average provided by tidal rhythmites of about half the modern value, these resonances will not be reached until about 3,000 and 4,000 million years, respectively.
[src:chandler-wobble/axial-precession] However, due to the gradually increasing luminosity of the Sun, the oceans of the Earth will have vaporized before that time (about 2,100 million years from now).
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] The **Chandler wobble** or **Chandler variation of latitude** is a small deviation in the Earth's axis of rotation relative to the solid earth, which was discovered by and named after American astronomer Seth Carlo Chandler in 1891.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] It amounts to change of about 9 metres (30 ft) in the point at which the axis intersects the Earth's surface and has a period of 433 days.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] This wobble, which is an astronomical nutation, combines with another wobble with a period of six years, so that the total polar motion varies with a period of about 7 years.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] The Chandler wobble is an example of the kind of motion that can occur for a freely rotating object that is not a sphere; this is called a free nutation.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] Somewhat confusingly, the direction of the Earth's rotation axis relative to the stars also varies with different periods, and these motions—caused by the tidal forces of the Moon and Sun—are also called nutations, except for the slowest, which are precessions of the equinoxes.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] The existence of Earth's free nutation was predicted by Isaac Newton in Corollaries 20 to 22 of Proposition 66, Book 1 of the *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica*, and by Leonhard Euler in 1765 as part of his studies of the dynamics of rotating bodies.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] Based on the known ellipticity of the Earth, Euler predicted that it would have a period of 305 days.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] Several astronomers searched for motions with this period, but none was found.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] Chandler's contribution was to look for motions at any possible period; once the Chandler wobble was observed, the difference between its period and the one predicted by Euler was explained by Simon Newcomb as being caused by the non-rigidity of the Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] The full explanation for the period also involves the fluid nature of the Earth's core and oceans—the wobble, in fact, produces a very small ocean tide with an amplitude of approximately 6 mm (1⁄4 in), called a *pole tide*, which is the only tide not caused by an extraterrestrial body.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] Despite the small amplitude, the gravitational effect of the pole tide is easily detected by the superconducting gravimeter.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] The International Latitude Observatories were established in 1899 to measure the wobble as observed in latitude determinations.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] These provided data on the Chandler and annual wobble for most of the 20th century, though they were eventually superseded by other methods of measurement.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] Monitoring of the polar motion is now done by the International Earth Rotation Service (IERS).
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] The wobble's amplitude has varied since its discovery, reaching its largest size in 1910 and fluctuating noticeably from one decade to another.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] In 2009, Malkin & Miller's analysis of IERS Pole coordinates time series data from January 1946 to January 2009 showed three phase reversals of the wobble, in 1850, 1920, and 2005.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] Measurements indicate the Chandler wobble has greatly diminished post-2015.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] Since the Earth is not a rigid body, the Chandler wobble should die down with a time constant of about 68 years, a very short period compared to geological timescales.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] (This is related to the Q factor of the oscillation.) The processes that continually re-excite the wobble are of interest to geophysicists.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] While it must be due to changes in the mass distribution or angular momentum of the Earth's outer core, atmosphere, oceans, or crust (from earthquakes), for a long time the actual source was unclear, since no available motions seemed to be coherent with what was driving the wobble.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] An investigation was done in 2001 by Richard Gross at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory managed by the California Institute of Technology.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] He used angular momentum models of the atmosphere and the oceans in computer simulations to show that from 1985 to 1996, the Chandler wobble was excited by a combination of atmospheric and oceanic processes, with the dominant excitation mechanism being ocean-bottom pressure fluctuations.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] Gross found that two-thirds of the "wobble" was caused by fluctuating pressure on the seabed, which, in turn, is caused by changes in the circulation of the oceans caused by variations in temperature, salinity, and wind.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] The remaining third is due to atmospheric pressure fluctuations.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] Using 18 years of radio tracking observations of the Mars Odyssey, Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter and the Mars Global Surveyor spacecraft, the Chandler wobble of Mars has been detected.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] It is the first time it has been detected on a planetary body other than the Earth.
[src:chandler-wobble/chandler-wobble] The amplitude is 10 cm, the period is 206.9 ± 0.5 days, and it is in a nearly circular counterclockwise direction as viewed from the North Pole.
